Next, we will convert the cost of production worth S$ 218.50 to U.S. using the new exchange rate.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Cost of Production \$} &= \dfrac{\text{S\$ to be exchanged}}{\text{Exchange Rate}}\\[10pt]
&= \dfrac{\text{S\$ 218.50}}{\text{S\$ 1.3781}}\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\text{\$ 158.55}}
\end{aligned}$$

Next, we will convert the cost of production worth S$ 218.50 to U.S. using the new exchange rate.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Cost of Production \$} &= \dfrac{\text{S\$ to be exchanged}}{\text{Exchange Rate}}\\[10pt]
&= \dfrac{\text{S\$ 218.50}}{\text{S\$ 1.1275}}\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\text{\$ 193.79}}
\end{aligned}$$

## c.

Next, we are asked to determine the break-even exchange rate. To determine the break-even exchange rate, we will divide the cost of production in Singapore dollar by the selling price in U.S. dollar. 

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Break-even exchange rate} &= \dfrac{\text{S\$ Cost of Production}}{\text{\$ Selling Price}}\\[10pt]
&= \dfrac{\text{S\$ 218.50}}{\text{\$ 185}}\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\text{S\$ 1.1811}}
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
The break-even exchange rate is **S$ 1.1811 per $1**.

To determine percentage rise or fall, first, we need to subtract the current exchange rate from the break-even exchange rate.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Difference } &= \text{Break-even Exchange Rate} - {\text{Current Exchange Rate}}\\
&= \text{S\$ 1.1811} - {\text{S\$ 1.2528}}\\
&=\boxed{\text{(S\$ 0.0717)}}
\end{aligned}$$

Next, we will divide the difference by the current exchange rate to get the percentage rise or fall.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage Rise (Fall)} &= \dfrac{\text{Difference in Exchange Rate}}{\text{Current Exchange Rate}}\\[10pt]
&= \dfrac{\text{(S\$ 0.0717)}}{\text{S\$ 1.2528}}\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\text{(5.72\%)}}
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
The **percentage fall by 5.72%** in terms of the Singapore dollar versus the U.S. dollar.
